The "original" Alatna first appeared as an unincorporated village on the 1920 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41084484v1ch5.pdf|format=PDF|title=Population|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref> At the time, it was located directly on the (north) west bank of the Yukon at {{Coord|66|33|44|N|152|40|20|W|region:US-AK_type:landmark_source:GNIS|name=Alatna, Alaska}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/66%C2%B033'44.2%22N+152%C2%B040'20.1%22W/@66.5585685,-152.6814975,3828m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d66.5622639!4d-152.6722407|title = Google Maps|website=Google.com}}</ref> a 1/2 mile west across the river from neighboring village [[Allakaket, Alaska|Allakaket]]. The population returns for 1930 combined Alatna and neighboring Allakaket, as the latter did not report a separate total.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/00476569ch2.pdf|format=PDF|title=Alaska|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref> In 1940<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/33973538v1ch11.pdf|format=PDF|title=Alaska : 1940 Census|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref>  and 1950,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41601749v2p51-54ch2.pdf|format=PDF|title=Number of Inhabitants : Alaska : 1950 Census|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref> the population was exclusively for Alatna. It did not appear on the 1960<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/37721577v1p3ch2.pdf|format=PDF|title=Number of Inhabitants : Alaska : 1960 Census|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref> or 1970<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1970a_ak-01.pdf|format=PDF|title=Number of Inhabitants : Alaska : 1970 Census|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref> census rolls. Allakaket incorporated in 1975 and included the village of Alatna within its boundaries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Allakaket,+AK/@66.5613916,-152.6820217,12.5z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x512980c57b68e5e7:0xb72342fa1f679acc!8m2!3d66.5655556!4d-152.6455556?hl=en|title = Allakaket · Alaska, USA|website=Google.com}}</ref> on the 1980 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1980a_akABCD-01.pdf|format=PDF|title=Number of Inhabitants : Alaska : 1970 Census|website=2.census.gov|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref> Alatna, however, was designated as an ANVSA (Alaskan Native Village Statistical Area) on the 1980 census (within the city of Allakaket), with 30 residents (29 of which were Native American). It appeared again in 1990 as a native village (ANVSA), again within Allakaket.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/prod/cen1990/cph5/cph-5-3.pdf |title=1990 Census of Population and Housing - Summary Social, Economic, and Housing Characteristics - Alaska |access-date=October 13, 2019 |archive-date=October 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201020144850/https://www.census.gov/prod/cen1990/cph5/cph-5-3.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1994, flooding of the Yukon River forced residents to relocate to higher ground a mile to the west, leaving the city limits of Allakaket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Alatna,+AK/@66.5478872,-152.8104239,11.62z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5129872b5aa884bb:0x501eed6395e2ecee!8m2!3d66.5572222!4d-152.7072221|title=Alatna · Alaska|website=Google.com|access-date=June 26, 2022}}</ref>

===(New) Alatna CDP (1994-)===
